  "prompt": "What happens to a non capsulated bacteria?",
  "response": "Non-capsulated bacteria generally lack a capsule, which is a protective layer outside their cell wall. This capsule plays a crucial role in bacterial survival and virulence. When bacteria lack a capsule, several things can happen:\n\n1. **Increased Vulnerability to Host Immune System**: The capsule provides a defense mechanism against the host's immune system. Non-capsulated bacteria are more easily recognized and destroyed by immune cells, such as macrophages and neutrophils.\n\n2. **Reduced Virulence**: The capsule helps in evading immune responses and contributes to the bacteria's ability to cause disease. Without a capsule, bacteria may have reduced virulence and may be less capable of establishing infections.\n\n3. **Susceptibility to Environmental Stress**: The capsule can protect bacteria from environmental stresses, including desiccation, harsh chemicals, and extreme temperatures. Non-capsulated bacteria may be less able to survive in such conditions.\n\n4. **Impacts on Physical Properties**: The capsule can also affect the physical properties of bacteria, such as their ability to form biofilms and their motility. Non-capsulated bacteria might have altered interactions with surfaces and may be less robust in biofilm formation.\n\nOverall, lacking a capsule generally makes bacteria more susceptible to host defenses and environmental challenges, potentially limiting their ability to thrive and cause disease.",
